20the%20Supreme%20Court%20suggested%20in%20January%202023%20that%20%E2%80%9Cpeople%20like%20Kavanaugh%20who%20the%20president%20fought%20for%2C%20who%20the%20president%20went%20through%20hell%20to%20get%20into%20place%2C%20he%E2%80%99ll%20step%20up.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnd%20Trump%20has%20questioned%20the%20credentials%20of%20most%20judges%20who%20have%20ruled%20against%20him%2C%20whether%20it%E2%80%99s%20in%20response%20to%20cases%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fapnews.com%2Farticle%2Fnorth-america-donald-trump-us-news-ap-top-news-immigration-c4b34f9639e141069c08cf1e3deb6b84%5C%22%3Einvolving%20his%20presidential%20policies%3C%2Fa%3E%20or%20those%20involving%20his%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftruthsocial.com%2F%40realDonaldTrump%2Fposts%2F111848593080388710%5C%22%3Epersonal%20conduct%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20especially%20when%20Democrats%20nominated%20those%20judges.%20When%20judges%20have%20refused%20to%20bend%20to%20his%20will%2C%20Trump%20has%20pushed%20back%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.brennancenter.org%2Four-work%2Fresearch-reports%2Fhis-own-words-presidents-attacks-courts%5C%22%3Elambasting%20the%20judges%3C%2Fa%3E%20as%20biased%20and%20saying%20they%20were%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2FrealDonaldTrump%2Fstatus%2F1065581119242940416%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9Cout%20of%20control%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20the%20court%20system%20was%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2FrealDonaldTrump%2Fstatus%2F951094078661414912%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9Cbroken%20and%20unfair.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fa%3E%20He%20used%20social%20media%20to%20call%20the%20federal%20judge%20presiding%20over%20his%20Jan.%206%20prosecution%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fabcnews.go.com%2FPolitics%2Fjudge-reinstates-trump-gag-order-jan-6-case%2Fstory%3Fid%3D104466343%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9CTRUE%20TRUMP%20HATER.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EIncreased%20criticism%2C%20decreased%20legitimacy%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFraming%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20as%20a%20political%20institution%20beholden%20to%20the%20president%20diminishes%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1177%2F1532673X211064299%5C%22%3Ecourt%E2%80%99s%20legitimacy%20in%20the%20eyes%20of%20the%20public%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Research%20shows%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1177%2F1065912917750278%5C%22%3Epeople%E2%80%99s%20support%20for%20the%20court%20decreases%3C%2Fa%3E%20when%20a%20politician%20they%20like%20criticizes%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESome%20people%20also%20struggle%20to%20believe%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2Fajps.12599%5C%22%3Ejudges%20who%20do%20not%20look%20or%20think%20like%20them%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20neutral%20arbiters%20of%20the%20law%2C%20so%20Trump%E2%80%99s%20comments%20potentially%20inflame%20those%20beliefs%20and%20increase%20people%E2%80%99s%20wariness%20of%20the%20judiciary.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBeyond%20that%2C%20Trump%20constantly%20tries%20to%20make%20the%20point%20that%20the%20entire%20judicial%20nominating%20process%20is%20political%2C%20from%20identifying%20judges%20by%20which%20president%20nominated%20them%20%E2%80%93%20for%20example%2C%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.politico.com%2Fstory%2F2018%2F11%2F21%2Fsupreme-court-chief-justice-john-roberts-calls-out-trump-for-his-attack-on-a-judge-1011203%2522%2522%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9CObama%20judge%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fa%3E%20or%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.huffpost.com%2Fentry%2Ftrump-judges-lawsuits_n_5db1d70ee4b03285e87ba2fd%2522%2522%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9CTrump%20judge%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%93%20to%20his%20leaning%20on%20the%20justices%20he%20put%20on%20the%20court.%20This%20has%20the%20broader%20effect%20of%20framing%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20as%20a%20political%20rather%20than%20legal%20institution.%20And%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2Fj.1540-5907.2012.00616.x%5C%22%3Edramatically%20decreases%20its%20legitimacy%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EPut%20simply%2C%20people%20support%20the%20court%20less%20when%20politicians%20attack%20it%2C%20and%20Trump%20frequently%20attacks%20the%20judiciary.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EMaintaining%20authority%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhy%20care%20about%20legitimacy%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBecause%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Favalon.law.yale.edu%2F18th_century%2Ffed78.asp%5C%22%3Eunlike%20the%20president%20or%20members%20of%20Congress%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20who%20can%20enforce%20their%20own%20laws%20and%20policies%20%E2%80%93%20as%20long%20as%20they%20abide%20by%20the%20Constitution%20%E2%80%93%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20depends%20on%20other%20institutions%20for%20enforcement%20of%20its%20opinions.%20The%20court%20lacks%20the%20literal%20force%20or%20money%20to%20enforce%20its%20decisions.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EConsider%20the%20Supreme%20Court%E2%80%99s%20famous%201954%20ruling%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oyez.org%2Fcases%2F1940-1955%2F347us483%5C%22%3EBrown%20v.%20Board%20of%20Education%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20ordered%20the%20end%20of%20school%20segregation.%20That%20ruling%20did%20not%20get%20enforced%20in%20most%20of%20the%20South%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2Fajps.12069%5C%22%3Euntil%20the%20president%20and%20Congress%20passed%20laws%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20punished%20schools%20that%20refused%20to%20integrate.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThose%20institutions%20enforce%20Supreme%20Court%20decisions%20only%20because%20the%20public%20believes%20the%20court%20is%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2F1540-5907.00025%5C%22%3Elegitimate%20legal%20institution%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20the%20authority%20to%20make%20decisions%20about%20the%20law%20and%20get%20them%20enforced.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20belief%20in%20judicial%20authority%20stems%20from%20several%20different%20sources%2C%20including%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.degruyter.com%2Fdocument%2Fdoi%2F10.1515%2F9781400830602%2Fhtml%5C%22%3Eelementary%20education%3C%2Fa%3E%20on%20democratic%20values%2C%20the%20justices%E2%80%99%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpress.umich.edu%2FBooks%2FT%2FThe-Limits-of-Legitimacy2%5C%22%3Econcerted%20efforts%3C%2Fa%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1177%2F1065912918801563%5C%22%3Eto%20avoid%3C%2Fa%3E%20all%20but%20the%20most%20favorable%20media%20attention%2C%20their%20focus%20on%20showing%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2Fj.1540-5907.2012.00616.x%5C%22%3Ethe%20principled%20nature%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20their%20decision-making%20process%2C%20their%20aim%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1017%2Fjlc.2023.15%5C%22%3Emitigate%20negative%20public%20sentiment%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20even%20their%20decision%20to%20separate%20themselves%20by%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2Flasr.12104%5C%22%3Ewearing%20robes%20to%20political%20events%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETo%20be%20sure%2C%20people%20are%20not%20naive%20about%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1146%2Fannurev-polisci-032211-214229%5C%22%3Epolitical%20nature%20of%20Supreme%20Court%20decision-making%3C%2Fa%3E.%20But%20as%20long%20as%20the%20justices%E2%80%99%20decision-making%20appears%20principled%2C%20research%20has%20found%20that%20the%20court%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1111%2Fj.1540-5893.2011.00432.x%5C%22%3Eremains%20legitimate%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20the%20public%2C%20even%20if%20the%20court%20issues%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1146%2Fannurev-lawsocsci-110413-030546%5C%22%3Edecision%20the%20public%20dislikes%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETypically%2C%20the%20justices%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpress.princeton.edu%2Fbooks%2Fpaperback%2F9780691136332%2Fthe-politics-of-precedent-on-the-us-supreme-court%5C%22%3Elean%20on%20precedent%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20defend%20their%20rulings%2C%20but%20the%20justices%20cannot%20do%20so%20in%20the%20Trump%20Colorado%20ballot%20case.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthehil